    cellular: { title: "Microbial Pathogenesis & Empiric Therapy Rationale", content: "Empiric antibiotic therapy is initiated before culture and sensitivity results are available, targeting the most likely pathogens based on the infection site, local antibiogram data, and patient-specific factors. Bacterial infections begin when organisms breach host defenses, adhere to tissue via surface adhesins, and proliferate. The choice of empiric agent depends on the expected pathogen spectrum: community-acquired pneumonia targets Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae, and atypical organisms; urinary tract infections target Escherichia coli and other gram-negative rods; skin and soft tissue infections target Staphylococcus aureus and Streptococcus pyogenes. Antimicrobial stewardship principles require narrowing therapy once culture results return, selecting the narrowest-spectrum effective agent, and monitoring for therapeutic failure or adverse effects including Clostridioides difficile infection." },
